# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1809-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] The **10th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1807, to March 4, 1809, during the seventh and eighth years of Thomas Jefferson's presidency.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 census; both chambers had an overwhelming Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] The count below identifies party affiliations at the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] Changes resulting from subsequent replacements are shown below in the "Changes in membership" section.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] This list is arranged by chamber, then by state.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed in order of seniority, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] Senators were elected by the state legislatures every two years, with one-third beginning new six-year terms with each Congress.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] Preceding the names in the list below are Senate class numbers, which indicate the cycle of their election.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their district numbers.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] The count below reflects changes from the beginning of the first session of this Congress.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] There were 5 resignations, 2 deaths, and 1 interim appointment.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 4 resignations, 4 deaths, and 2 vacancies from the beginning of this Congress.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] Democratic-Republicans had no net change and Federalists picked up 2 seats.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/10th-united-states-congress] Lists of committees and their party leaders.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] The **11th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, consisting of the United States Senate and the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] It met in Washington, D.C., from March 4, 1809, to March 4, 1811, during the first two years of James Madison's presidency.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] The apportionment of seats in the House of Representatives was based on the 1800 United States census.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Both chambers had a Democratic-Republican majority.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Senators are listed by class, and representatives are listed by district.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] In this Congress, Class 1 meant their term began with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1814; Class 2 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring re-election in 1810; and Class 3 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring re-election in 1812.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] The names of representatives are preceded by their districts.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] There were 8 resignations, 2 deaths, 1 interim appointment, and 1 vacancy from before this Congress.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/11th-united-states-congress] Of the voting members, there were 12 resignations, 1 death, and 1 change due to a contested election.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/1737-in-great-britain] Events from the year **1737 in Great Britain**.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/1752] In the British Empire, it was the only year with 355 days: the 11 days from 3 to 13 September were dropped when the Empire adopted the Gregorian calendar.
[src:1809-in-the-united-states/1809-in-the-united-states] Events from the year **1809 in the United States**.
